{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95c9ef43-322e-4feb-8e79-50b491d0fdba","content":"\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** property called `SafeAreaRegions` directly on `Page`.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n```\n\nYou can drop the `xmlns:ios` namespace entirely if that was its only use. The `SafeAreaRegions` property is a flags enum, so you can also be selective:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Only respect safe area at top and bottom -->\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"Top,Bottom\">\n```\n\nValid values: `None`, `All`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3605d112-4f9d-4e4b-9240-688244db7c5c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a knowledge question about a framework change.\n\nIn .NET 10 (which would be a preview/RC at this point in April 2026), there were changes to how safe area insets are handled in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI for .NET 9 and earlier, the iOS-specific `Page.UseSafeArea` property was used to automatically pad content away from the status bar, notch, and home indicator areas. The API was `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, Microsoft shifted to a cross-platform `SafeAreaRegions` property on the `Page` class instead of the iOS-specific approach, using a flags enum with options like `All`, `None`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, and `Right` to handle safe areas consistently across platforms including Android devices with cutouts. I should clarify what the actual migration path looks like and provide the correct XAML syntax for .NET 10. In .NET 10, the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` property was replaced with a cross-platform `SafeAreaRegions` property on the `Page` class, moving away from platform-specific XML namespaces toward a unified approach.","outputTokens":1169},"id":"bdebbbe5-0ca2-4fcf-a0d5-123353ffea4a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:42.104Z","parentId":"65b0f3f2-e435-4149-a781-2c8424d3b2cc"}
